                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d847">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">836.48 1930 Hurricane/32: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-09-09T12:00:00-04:40"
                            >September 9, 1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. My 103 September 9, 11 a.m.<note n="18" xml:id="d847fn18">Not
                        printed.</note> Dominican Army and police are almost completely demoralized
                    and the moral effect of having 50 marines here would be enormously beneficial.
                    Major W. B. Sullivan who has acted as Navy Department liaison officer states
                    that Trujillo requests me through him to have such detachment sent here. Major
                    Sullivan particularly recommends sending also Captain Thomas E. Watson, United
                    States Marine Corps.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Curtis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
